To incorporate autocomplete by Algolia into a Next.js app, you can follow these steps:

1. Install the Algolia JavaScript client library by running the following command in your Next.js project directory:

```
npm install algoliasearch
```

2. Create a new component for the autocomplete functionality. You can create a new file called Autocomplete.js in your components directory and add the following code:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import algoliasearch from 'algoliasearch';

const client = algoliasearch('YOUR_APP_ID', 'YOUR_SEARCH_API_KEY');
const index = client.initIndex('YOUR_INDEX_NAME');

const Autocomplete = () => {
  const [query, setQuery] = useState('');
  const [results, setResults] = useState([]);

  const handleInputChange = async (e) => {
    const inputValue = e.target.value;
    setQuery(inputValue);

    if (inputValue.length > 0) {
      const { hits } = await index.search(inputValue);
      setResults(hits);
    } else {
      setResults([]);
    }
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <input
        type="text"
        value={query}
        onChange={handleInputChange}
        placeholder="Search..."
      />
      <ul>
        {results.map((result) => (
          <li key={result.objectID}>{result.name}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
};

export default Autocomplete;
```

3. Import and use the Autocomplete component in your Next.js pages. For example, you can add the Autocomplete component to your index.js page like this:

```jsx
import Autocomplete from '../components/Autocomplete';

const Home = () => {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Next.js App with Algolia Autocomplete</h1>
      <Autocomplete />
    </div>
  );
};

export default Home;
```

4. Replace 'YOUR_APP_ID', 'YOUR_SEARCH_API_KEY', and 'YOUR_INDEX_NAME' with your actual Algolia application ID, search API key, and index name.

5. Start your Next.js app by running the following command in your project directory:

```
npm run dev
```

Now, you should have autocomplete functionality powered by Algolia in your Next.js app. Users can type in the search input field, and the autocomplete results will be displayed below the input field based on the search query.

