You can achieve this by using Spring's `@ConditionalOnProperty` annotation in your service configuration classes. 

First, define a property in your `application.properties` file that specifies which service implementation to use. For example:

```
myapp.service.type=service1
```

Then, in your service configuration classes, use the `@ConditionalOnProperty` annotation to conditionally load the service implementation based on the value of the property:

```java
@Configuration
public class ServiceConfig {

    @Bean
    @ConditionalOnProperty(name = "myapp.service.type", havingValue = "service1")
    public MyService myService1() {
        return new Service1();
    }

    @Bean
    @ConditionalOnProperty(name = "myapp.service.type", havingValue = "service2")
    public MyService myService2() {
        return new Service2();
    }
}
```

In this example, `Service1` and `Service2` are two different implementations of the `MyService` interface. Depending on the value of the `myapp.service.type` property, either `myService1` or `myService2` bean will be loaded.

Make sure to annotate your main application class with `@SpringBootApplication` and include the `@ComponentScan` annotation to scan the package where your service configuration classes are located. 

```
@SpringBootApplication
@ComponentScan("com.example.services")
public class MyAppApplication {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(MyAppApplication.class, args);
    }
}
```

Now, when you start your Spring Boot application, it will load the service implementation based on the value of the `myapp.service.type` property.

