You can achieve this by using the HTMLCanvasElement to draw the content of the HTML node onto a canvas element, and then converting the canvas to an image that can be copied to the clipboard. Here is an example code snippet to demonstrate this:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Copy HTML Node as Image</title>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="nodeToCopy">
        <h1>Hello, World!</h1>
        <p>This is an example HTML node to copy as an image.</p>
    </div>

    <button onclick="copyNodeAsImage()">Copy Node as Image</button>

    <script>
        function copyNodeAsImage() {
            const nodeToCopy = document.getElementById('nodeToCopy');
            const canvas = document.createElement('canvas');
            const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');

            canvas.width = nodeToCopy.offsetWidth;
            canvas.height = nodeToCopy.offsetHeight;

            const data = new XMLSerializer().serializeToString(nodeToCopy);
            const img = new Image();
            img.src = 'data:image/svg+xml;base64,' + btoa(data);

            img.onload = function() {
                ctx.drawImage(img, 0, 0);

                canvas.toBlob(function(blob) {
                    const item = new ClipboardItem({ 'image/png': blob });
                    navigator.clipboard.write([item]).then(function() {
                        console.log('Node copied as image to clipboard');
                    }).catch(function(error) {
                        console.error('Failed to copy node as image to clipboard:', error);
                    });
                }, 'image/png');
            };
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In this code snippet, we first create a canvas element and draw the content of the HTML node onto it as an image. We then convert the canvas to a blob and create a ClipboardItem with the image data. Finally, we use the Clipboard API to write the image data to the clipboard.

