```

2. Compile the regex pattern using the `pcre_compile` function:

```cpp
const char *pattern = "your_regex_pattern_here";
const char *error;
int error_offset;
pcre *re = pcre_compile(pattern, 0, &error, &error_offset, NULL);
if (re == NULL) {
    // Handle compilation error
    std::cerr << "Error compiling regex: " << error << " at offset " << error_offset << std::endl;
    return 1;
}
```

3. Once the regex is compiled, you can reuse it to match against a string using the `pcre_exec` function:

```cpp
const char *subject = "your_input_string_here";
int rc;
int ovector[30]; // This array will hold the matched substring offsets

rc = pcre_exec(re, NULL, subject, strlen(subject), 0, 0, ovector, 30);
if (rc < 0) {
    switch (rc) {
        case PCRE_ERROR_NOMATCH:
            // Handle no match
            break;
        default:
            // Handle other errors
            std::cerr << "Error matching regex: " << rc << std::endl;
            break;
    }
} else {
    // Match found, process the matched substrings
    for (int i = 0; i < rc; i++) {
        int start = ovector[2*i];
        int end = ovector[2*i+1];
        std::string matched(subject + start, end - start);
        std::cout << "Matched substring: " << matched << std::endl;
    }
}
```

4. Finally, don't forget to free the compiled regex using the `pcre_free` function when you're done with it:

```cpp
pcre_free(re);
```

By following these steps, you can compile a regex pattern once and reuse it multiple times in your C++ code using PCRE.

