class TokenBucket {
  private capacity: number;
  private tokens: number;
  private lastRefillTime: number;
  private refillRate: number;

  constructor(capacity: number, refillRate: number) {
    this.capacity = capacity;
    this.tokens = capacity;
    this.lastRefillTime = Date.now();
    this.refillRate = refillRate;
  }

  private refill() {
    const now = Date.now();
    const elapsedTime = now - this.lastRefillTime;
    const tokensToAdd = elapsedTime * (this.refillRate / 1000);
    this.tokens = Math.min(this.capacity, this.tokens + tokensToAdd);
    this.lastRefillTime = now;
  }

  public takeToken(): boolean {
    this.refill();
    if (this.tokens >= 1) {
      this.tokens--;
      return true;
    } else {
      return false;
    }
  }
}

// Example usage
const bucket = new TokenBucket(10, 1); // 10 tokens, refill rate of 1 token per second

for (let i = 0; i < 15; i++) {
  if (bucket.takeToken()) {
    console.log(`Token ${i + 1} taken`);
  } else {
    console.log(`Token ${i + 1} not taken - rate limited`);
  }
}
```

In this implementation, the `TokenBucket` class has a `capacity` which represents the maximum number of tokens the bucket can hold, a `tokens` property which represents the current number of tokens in the bucket, a `lastRefillTime` property to keep track of the last time the bucket was refilled, and a `refillRate` property which determines how many tokens are added to the bucket per second.

The `refill` method calculates the number of tokens to add to the bucket based on the elapsed time since the last refill and the refill rate. The `takeToken` method checks if there are enough tokens in the bucket to take one, refills the bucket if necessary, and returns true if a token was taken successfully, or false if the rate limit was exceeded.

The example usage demonstrates taking tokens from the bucket and handling rate limiting when the bucket runs out of tokens.
